## Findings
### Finding 1: searchClients tenant isolation is untested
**Severity**: CRITICAL
**Category**: missing-test
**Location**: src/api/controllers/clientController.ts:13 / test-file: missing
**Criticality Score**: 9
**Issue**: No test verifies that search only returns the caller's tenant's clients. In a multi-tenant app, a regression here leaks PII across tenants.
**Untested Code**:
```ts
const clients = await prisma.client.findMany({ where: { tenantId: req.tenantId, name: { contains: q, mode: 'insensitive' } } });
```
**Why This Matters**: A future change to the where clause could drop the tenant filter; without a cross-tenant test it ships silently and exposes another tenant's clients.
**Test Suggestions**:
| Option | Approach | Catches | Effort |
| A | Supertest: seed two tenants, assert search only returns caller's | Cross-tenant leakage, filter correctness | MED |
| B | Unit-mock prisma, assert where.tenantId passed | Wrong arg wiring only | LOW |
**Recommended**: Option A
**Reasoning**: Integration test verifies real behavior (the actual query result), not the implementation detail of which args were passed — aligns with behavior-not-implementation and the existing Supertest pattern.
**Recommended Test**:
```ts
it('returns only the calling tenant\'s clients', async () => {
  // Arrange
  await seedClient({ tenantId: 'tA', name: 'Acme' });
  await seedClient({ tenantId: 'tB', name: 'Acme' });
  // Act
  const res = await request(app).get('/clients/search?q=Acme').set(authHeader('tA'));
  // Assert
  expect(res.status).toBe(200);
  expect(res.body).toHaveLength(1);
  expect(res.body[0].tenantId).toBe('tA');
});
```
**Test Pattern Reference**:
```ts
// SOURCE: src/api/controllers/invoiceController.test.ts:22-31
it('lists only tenant invoices', async () => {
  const res = await request(app).get('/invoices').set(authHeader('tA'));
  expect(res.body.every(i => i.tenantId === 'tA')).toBe(true);
});
```

### Finding 2: deleteClient not-found and idempotency paths untested
**Severity**: HIGH
**Category**: missing-edge-case
**Location**: src/api/controllers/clientController.ts:20 / test-file: missing
**Criticality Score**: 7
**Issue**: No test covers deleting a non-existent id (should be 404 once awaited) or deleting twice (idempotency), the exact failure modes the un-awaited delete introduces.
**Untested Code**:
```ts
await prisma.client.delete({ where: { id, tenantId: req.tenantId } });
res.status(204).send();
```
**Why This Matters**: Without these tests the false-204 silent-failure bug can regress unnoticed; users would again get success on a no-op delete.
**Test Suggestions**:
| Option | Approach | Catches | Effort |
| A | Supertest: delete missing id → expect 404 | Missing error mapping, false 204 | LOW |
| B | Spy on prisma.delete rejection | Implementation coupling | LOW |
**Recommended**: Option A
**Reasoning**: Asserting the HTTP status for a missing id tests observable behavior and directly guards the silent-failure defect; spying on the mock couples the test to internals (DAMP violation).
**Recommended Test**:
```ts
it('returns 404 when deleting a non-existent client', async () => {
  // Arrange
  const missingId = 'does-not-exist';
  // Act
  const res = await request(app).delete(`/clients/${missingId}`).set(authHeader('tA'));
  // Assert
  expect(res.status).toBe(404);
});
```
**Test Pattern Reference**:
```ts
// SOURCE: src/api/controllers/invoiceController.test.ts:48-52
it('404s on missing invoice delete', async () => {
  const res = await request(app).delete('/invoices/nope').set(authHeader('tA'));
  expect(res.status).toBe(404);
});
```

